[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":763},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F08\u002F15\u002Fjavascript-core-27-object-reference-in-action\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F08\u002F15\u002Fjavascript-core-27-object-reference-in-action\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F08\u002F15\u002Fjavascript-core-27-object-reference-in-action\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F08\u002F15\u002Fjavascript-core-27-object-reference-in-action\u002F":738,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F08\u002F15\u002Fjavascript-core-27-object-reference-in-action\u002F":747},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200815\u002F1875070167\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":721,"date":722,"description":723,"extension":724,"lang":725,"meta":726,"navigation":65,"path":727,"readingMinutes":728,"seo":729,"standalone":730,"stem":731,"tags":732,"tldr":735,"updated":722,"url":736,"__hash__":737},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-27-object-reference-in-action.md","JavaScript Core Concepts (27) — Objects: How Object References Actually Work","1000839417",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":715},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,98,101,108,115,132,138,152,185,191,194,200,216,263,269,278,282,289,316,319,397,410,416,419,433,439,442,448,466,472,498,562,565,677,680,686,689,695,699,711],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Last time we talked about pass-by-reference for objects, but honestly the explanation was still pretty fuzzy. So this time let's actually dig into how it works.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"how-primitives-work","How primitives work",[17,25,26],{},"Let's start with a simple example.",[28,29,34],"pre",{"className":30,"code":31,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var a = 'Ray';\n\nvar b = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n};\n","js","",[35,36,37,60,67,80,92],"code",{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,39,42,46,50,53,57],"span",{"class":40,"line":41},"line",1,[38,43,45],{"class":44},"sWyjQ","var",[38,47,49],{"class":48},"sMAXC"," a ",[38,51,52],{"class":44},"=",[38,54,56],{"class":55},"sTRMh"," 'Ray'",[38,58,59],{"class":48},";\n",[38,61,63],{"class":40,"line":62},2,[38,64,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},true,"\n",[38,68,70,72,75,77],{"class":40,"line":69},3,[38,71,45],{"class":44},[38,73,74],{"class":48}," b ",[38,76,52],{"class":44},[38,78,79],{"class":48}," {\n",[38,81,83,86,89],{"class":40,"line":82},4,[38,84,85],{"class":48},"  name: ",[38,87,88],{"class":55},"'Ray'",[38,90,91],{"class":48},",\n",[38,93,95],{"class":40,"line":94},5,[38,96,97],{"class":48},"};\n",[17,99,100],{},"There are two things going on here — one is a primitive, the other is an object. Let me draw some diagrams to show how each one behaves.",[17,102,103,104,107],{},"When the code first runs, JavaScript sets up both variables and points them at ",[35,105,106],{},"undefined"," (this is hoisting, so nothing too surprising here).",[17,109,110],{},[111,112],"img",{"alt":113,"src":114},"pointing at undefined","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-15%2022.46.57.png",[17,116,117,118,121,122,125,126,128,129,131],{},"Next, JavaScript reserves a chunk of memory to hold our primitive value. ",[35,119,120],{},"a"," points at that memory chunk — let's say it's ",[35,123,124],{},"0x01",". So really, ",[35,127,120],{}," just grabs the address ",[35,130,124],{}," and gets that value back.",[17,133,134],{},[111,135],{"alt":136,"src":137},"memory space","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-15%2022.53.51.png",[17,139,140,141,144,145,147,148,151],{},"Now we do ",[35,142,143],{},"var c = a;"," to copy ",[35,146,120],{}," into ",[35,149,150],{},"c",". The thing to notice here: when you assign a primitive to another variable, it points at the same memory chunk and copies the value over.",[28,153,155],{"className":30,"code":154,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var a = 'Ray';\n\nvar c = a;\n",[35,156,157,169,173],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,158,159,161,163,165,167],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,160,45],{"class":44},[38,162,49],{"class":48},[38,164,52],{"class":44},[38,166,56],{"class":55},[38,168,59],{"class":48},[38,170,171],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,172,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,174,175,177,180,182],{"class":40,"line":69},[38,176,45],{"class":44},[38,178,179],{"class":48}," c ",[38,181,52],{"class":44},[38,183,184],{"class":48}," a;\n",[17,186,187],{},[111,188],{"alt":189,"src":190},"pointing at the same memory space","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-15%2023.00.07.png",[17,192,193],{},"I'm guessing this is already getting confusing, so here's an animation to make it clearer.",[17,195,196],{},[111,197],{"alt":198,"src":199},"animated version","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E7%B4%94%E5%80%BC%E6%8C%87%E5%90%91.gif",[17,201,202,203,205,206,208,209,211,212,215],{},"So when you change the value of ",[35,204,150],{},", it doesn't affect ",[35,207,120],{}," — because ",[35,210,150],{}," now points at a different memory chunk called ",[35,213,214],{},"0x02",".",[28,217,219],{"className":30,"code":218,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var a = 'Ray';\n\nvar c = a;\n\nc = '123';\n",[35,220,221,233,237,247,251],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,222,223,225,227,229,231],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,224,45],{"class":44},[38,226,49],{"class":48},[38,228,52],{"class":44},[38,230,56],{"class":55},[38,232,59],{"class":48},[38,234,235],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,236,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,238,239,241,243,245],{"class":40,"line":69},[38,240,45],{"class":44},[38,242,179],{"class":48},[38,244,52],{"class":44},[38,246,184],{"class":48},[38,248,249],{"class":40,"line":82},[38,250,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,252,253,256,258,261],{"class":40,"line":94},[38,254,255],{"class":48},"c ",[38,257,52],{"class":44},[38,259,260],{"class":55}," '123'",[38,262,59],{"class":48},[17,264,265],{},[111,266],{"alt":267,"src":268},"new memory space","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-15%2023.08.00.png",[17,270,271,272,274,275,277],{},"That's exactly why changing ",[35,273,150],{}," doesn't touch ",[35,276,120],{}," — they live in different memory spaces.",[12,279,281],{"id":280},"pass-by-reference-for-objects","Pass-by-reference for objects",[17,283,284,285,288],{},"Now for the trickier part: objects. With objects, basically once you see a variable followed by ",[35,286,287],{},"{ }",", you know it's an object.",[28,290,292],{"className":30,"code":291,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var b = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n};\n",[35,293,294,304,312],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,295,296,298,300,302],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,297,45],{"class":44},[38,299,74],{"class":48},[38,301,52],{"class":44},[38,303,79],{"class":48},[38,305,306,308,310],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,307,85],{"class":48},[38,309,88],{"class":55},[38,311,91],{"class":48},[38,313,314],{"class":40,"line":69},[38,315,97],{"class":48},[17,317,318],{},"And we know objects have this thing called \"pass-by-reference\". Like the name says, once you assign an object to another variable and then change a property inside it, the original property gets changed too.",[28,320,322],{"className":30,"code":321,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var b = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n};\n\nvar e = b;\n\ne.name = 'QQ';\nconsole.log(b.name); \u002F\u002F QQ\n",[35,323,324,334,342,346,350,362,367,380],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,325,326,328,330,332],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,327,45],{"class":44},[38,329,74],{"class":48},[38,331,52],{"class":44},[38,333,79],{"class":48},[38,335,336,338,340],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,337,85],{"class":48},[38,339,88],{"class":55},[38,341,91],{"class":48},[38,343,344],{"class":40,"line":69},[38,345,97],{"class":48},[38,347,348],{"class":40,"line":82},[38,349,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,351,352,354,357,359],{"class":40,"line":94},[38,353,45],{"class":44},[38,355,356],{"class":48}," e ",[38,358,52],{"class":44},[38,360,361],{"class":48}," b;\n",[38,363,365],{"class":40,"line":364},6,[38,366,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,368,370,373,375,378],{"class":40,"line":369},7,[38,371,372],{"class":48},"e.name ",[38,374,52],{"class":44},[38,376,377],{"class":55}," 'QQ'",[38,379,59],{"class":48},[38,381,383,386,390,393],{"class":40,"line":382},8,[38,384,385],{"class":48},"console.",[38,387,389],{"class":388},"sj_SG","log",[38,391,392],{"class":48},"(b.name); ",[38,394,396],{"class":395},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F QQ\n",[17,398,399,400,402,403,405,406,409],{},"So what's happening here in terms of memory and pointers? First, ",[35,401,287],{}," creates a memory chunk (I'll skip the ",[35,404,106],{}," part this time) — let's say it's ",[35,407,408],{},"0x03"," — and the variable points at it.",[17,411,412],{},[111,413],{"alt":414,"src":415},"object memory pointer","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-15%2023.43.57.png",[17,417,418],{},"So far so good — this part is a lot like the primitive case.",[17,420,421,422,425,426,428,429,432],{},"But the key thing is the properties. Right now a property is basically a primitive concept: each property has its own memory chunk. ",[35,423,424],{},"name"," is a property that only lives inside this ",[35,427,408],{}," chunk, and it points at yet another memory chunk — say ",[35,430,431],{},"0x04",". The idea here is very similar to primitives.",[17,434,435],{},[111,436],{"alt":437,"src":438},"property memory pointer","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-15%2023.52.51.png",[17,440,441],{},"I'm pretty sure the pointer stuff is getting messy by now, so here's an animation too.",[17,443,444],{},[111,445],{"alt":446,"src":447},"animated memory pointers","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E7%89%A9%E4%BB%B6%E8%A8%98%E6%86%B6%E9%AB%94%E6%8C%87%E5%90%91.gif",[17,449,450,451,454,455,457,458,461,462,465],{},"So now let's talk about why, when we do ",[35,452,453],{},"var e = b;"," and change the ",[35,456,424],{}," property, the original object gets changed too. First, we create the variable ",[35,459,460],{},"e",", and its memory pointer points at ",[35,463,464],{},"b","'s memory address. No big deal so far.",[17,467,468],{},[111,469],{"alt":470,"src":471},"variable e pointing at variable b's memory space","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-16%2000.05.38.png",[17,473,474,475,477,478,481,482,484,485,487,488,490,491,494,495,497],{},"Now here's the key part. As you can see in the image above, our memory pointer keeps pointing at ",[35,476,408],{},". So when we operate on ",[35,479,480],{},"e.name",", we're really operating on the ",[35,483,431],{}," memory chunk that the ",[35,486,424],{}," property under ",[35,489,408],{}," points to. That's exactly why ",[35,492,493],{},"e.name = 'Ray'"," ends up affecting the original ",[35,496,464],{}," object — from start to finish it's the same memory being pointed at.",[28,499,500],{"className":30,"code":321,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},[35,501,502,512,520,524,528,538,542,552],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,503,504,506,508,510],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,505,45],{"class":44},[38,507,74],{"class":48},[38,509,52],{"class":44},[38,511,79],{"class":48},[38,513,514,516,518],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,515,85],{"class":48},[38,517,88],{"class":55},[38,519,91],{"class":48},[38,521,522],{"class":40,"line":69},[38,523,97],{"class":48},[38,525,526],{"class":40,"line":82},[38,527,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,529,530,532,534,536],{"class":40,"line":94},[38,531,45],{"class":44},[38,533,356],{"class":48},[38,535,52],{"class":44},[38,537,361],{"class":48},[38,539,540],{"class":40,"line":364},[38,541,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,543,544,546,548,550],{"class":40,"line":369},[38,545,372],{"class":48},[38,547,52],{"class":44},[38,549,377],{"class":55},[38,551,59],{"class":48},[38,553,554,556,558,560],{"class":40,"line":382},[38,555,385],{"class":48},[38,557,389],{"class":388},[38,559,392],{"class":48},[38,561,396],{"class":395},[17,563,564],{},"So if you want to create a brand-new object space, declare a new object or assign a fresh object. That way you avoid the pass-by-reference situation, because now the memory chunks are all different.",[28,566,568],{"className":30,"code":567,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var b = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n};\n\nvar e = b;\n\ne = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n};\n\ne.name = 'QQ';\n\nconsole.log(b.name); \u002F\u002F Ray\nconsole.log(e.name); \u002F\u002F QQ\n",[35,569,570,580,588,592,596,606,610,619,627,632,637,648,653,665],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,571,572,574,576,578],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,573,45],{"class":44},[38,575,74],{"class":48},[38,577,52],{"class":44},[38,579,79],{"class":48},[38,581,582,584,586],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,583,85],{"class":48},[38,585,88],{"class":55},[38,587,91],{"class":48},[38,589,590],{"class":40,"line":69},[38,591,97],{"class":48},[38,593,594],{"class":40,"line":82},[38,595,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,597,598,600,602,604],{"class":40,"line":94},[38,599,45],{"class":44},[38,601,356],{"class":48},[38,603,52],{"class":44},[38,605,361],{"class":48},[38,607,608],{"class":40,"line":364},[38,609,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,611,612,615,617],{"class":40,"line":369},[38,613,614],{"class":48},"e ",[38,616,52],{"class":44},[38,618,79],{"class":48},[38,620,621,623,625],{"class":40,"line":382},[38,622,85],{"class":48},[38,624,88],{"class":55},[38,626,91],{"class":48},[38,628,630],{"class":40,"line":629},9,[38,631,97],{"class":48},[38,633,635],{"class":40,"line":634},10,[38,636,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,638,640,642,644,646],{"class":40,"line":639},11,[38,641,372],{"class":48},[38,643,52],{"class":44},[38,645,377],{"class":55},[38,647,59],{"class":48},[38,649,651],{"class":40,"line":650},12,[38,652,66],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":65},[38,654,656,658,660,662],{"class":40,"line":655},13,[38,657,385],{"class":48},[38,659,389],{"class":388},[38,661,392],{"class":48},[38,663,664],{"class":395},"\u002F\u002F Ray\n",[38,666,668,670,672,675],{"class":40,"line":667},14,[38,669,385],{"class":48},[38,671,389],{"class":388},[38,673,674],{"class":48},"(e.name); ",[38,676,396],{"class":395},[17,678,679],{},"Finally, here are the memory-pointer diagram and animation to wrap up.",[17,681,682],{},[111,683],{"alt":684,"src":685},"reassigning a new object","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-16%2000.28.48.png",[17,687,688],{},"And the animated version of the memory pointers:",[17,690,691],{},[111,692],{"alt":693,"src":694},"new object memory pointer","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%96%B0%E7%9A%84%E7%89%A9%E4%BB%B6%E8%A8%98%E6%86%B6%E9%AB%94%E5%8F%83%E8%80%83.gif",[12,696,698],{"id":697},"references","References",[700,701,702],"ul",{},[703,704,705],"li",{},[120,706,710],{"href":707,"rel":708},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hexschool.com\u002Fcourses\u002Fjs-core.html",[709],"nofollow","JavaScript Core (course in Mandarin)",[712,713,714],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}",{"title":33,"searchDepth":62,"depth":62,"links":716},[717,718,719,720],{"id":14,"depth":62,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":62,"text":23},{"id":280,"depth":62,"text":281},{"id":697,"depth":62,"text":698},"JavaScript","2020-08-15 23:24:32","Last time we talked about pass-by-reference for objects, but the explanation was still pretty fuzzy. So this time let's actually see how it works under the hood — what happens in memory when you copy a primitive, and what happens when you assign an object to another variable and change its properties.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fjavascript-core-27-object-reference-in-action","3",{"title":6,"description":723},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-27-object-reference-in-action",[721,733,734],"JavaScript Core","Object",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F08\u002F15\u002Fjavascript-core-27-object-reference-in-action\u002F","3lALya9HOognpcoQ4jd9oo8vCpNPxNAi4R9N4PCQsFg",{"newer":739,"older":743},{"url":740,"title":741,"date":742},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F08\u002F17\u002Fpixijs-v5-28-load-images-from-json\u002F","PixiJS V5 Tutorial (28) - Loading Images from JSON","2020-08-17 08:30:47",{"url":744,"title":745,"date":746},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F08\u002F10\u002Fpixijs-v5-27-crop-sprite-texture\u002F","PixiJS V5 Tutorial (27) - Cropping Images with Rectangle and Texture","2020-08-10 08:34:32",[748,753,758],{"url":749,"title":750,"date":751,"readingMinutes":752},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F10\u002Fweb-crypto-api-encryption-guide\u002F","No crypto Package, No Node.js — The Web Crypto API Does It All in the Browser","2026-03-10 09:45:08","9",{"url":754,"title":755,"date":756,"readingMinutes":757},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fjquery-why-it-declined\u002F","jQuery Was Once King — So Why Did It Fall Off?","2025-12-08 21:35:24","7",{"url":759,"title":760,"date":761,"readingMinutes":762},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-generator-functions\u002F","What Are JavaScript Generator Functions (function*)? The Function You Can Pause and Resume","2025-12-05 13:40:31","5",1784011701474]